This problem will use this new proposed model to determine the effect of the two marginal tax rates on the share price.

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{(\text{P}_O-\text{P}_x)}{\text{D}}&=\dfrac{1-\text{T}_P}{1-\text{T}_G}
\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_O&=\text{Price before the stock goes ex}\\
\text{P}_x&=\text{Ex-dividend share price}\\
\text{D}&=\text{Dividend}\\
\text{T}_P&=\text{Marginal personal tax rate}\\
\text{T}_G&=\text{Marginal tax rate on capital gains}
\end{aligned}$$

It is also important to note that ex means that the stock is still trading without the value of the next dividend payment.

**a.)** In the first case, the given condition is $\text{T}_P=\text{T}_G=0$ which means that both the marginal tax rates are equal to zero. Substituting these in the formula, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{(\text{P}_O-\text{P}_x)}{\text{D}}&=\dfrac{1-0}{1-0}\\[15 pt]
\text{P}_O-\text{P}_x&=\text{D}
\end{aligned}$$

This shows that if both marginal rates are zero, the price change of the share will be equal to the dividend.

**b.)** In this next case, the marginal personal tax rate is $15\%$ and the marginal tax rate on capital gains is zero. Substituting these to the formula, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
\dfrac{(\text{P}_O-\text{P}_x)}{\text{D}}&=\dfrac{1-0.15}{1-0}\\[15 pt]
\text{P}_O-\text{P}_x&=0.85\text{D}
\end{aligned}$$

This means that the price change will be $85\%$ of the declared dividends.
